---
description: Real-time engine — Socket.IO events, Twilio media stream handler
globs: backend/app/realtime/**, frontend/src/lib/socket.ts, frontend/src/stores/call-store.ts
---

Real-time stack:
- python-socketio (async) mounted on the FastAPI ASGI app.
- Redis Pub/Sub as the transport between Celery workers/services and Socket.IO server.
- Socket.IO Client (frontend) for receiving live updates.

Real-time event types in SalesIQ:
- `transcript:chunk` — new transcription segment during a live call.
- `analysis:sentiment` — real-time sentiment score update.
- `analysis:guidance` — AI-suggested talking point or objection-handling tip.
- `analysis:redflag` — red flag alert (competitor mention, pricing objection, negative sentiment).
- `call:started`, `call:ended` — call lifecycle events.
- `notification:new` — general notification for agents/admins.

Architecture:
- Twilio Media Streams deliver raw audio via WebSocket to backend/app/realtime/call_stream_handler.py.
- The stream handler processes audio, calls Whisper, calls GPT-4o, and publishes results to Redis.
- Socket.IO server subscribes to Redis channels and forwards events to connected frontend clients.
- Frontend stores (call-store, notification-store) update reactively on Socket.IO events.

Rules:
- Keep Socket.IO event handlers thin; delegate to services for business logic.
- Use rooms/namespaces for tenant and call isolation (e.g. room per call_id).
- Authenticate Socket.IO connections with JWT.
- Handle reconnection gracefully on both client and server.
- Event payloads should be typed (Pydantic on backend, TypeScript interfaces on frontend).

Do not:
- Put heavy computation in Socket.IO event handlers.
- Send unscoped events (always scope by tenant/call).
- Allow unauthenticated Socket.IO connections.
- Mix REST API logic with real-time event handling in the same file.
